It's great that you're exploring your own identity and that you are supportive of your diverse group of friends. It's also great that you are trying to explain things to your parents to both educate them and make them more accepting of people who are different from them. I understand you got upset by your dad's comment, but he was really more just bitching about it being complicated than actually being bigoted or intentionally hurtful. Could he be more tolerant and understanding? Yes. But in the grand scheme of things he's not harming anyone, he's just wishing it was simpler. It's not. It's complicated. Maybe one day he'll understand and maybe he won't but it's not worth you getting upset over. Save that level of upset for the many people in the world who hate everyone in the LGBTQIA+ community and spread hatred. This is not your dad.

Also, just for your own knowledge, being pan is a sexuality. That's just who you are. Being poly is a lifestyle choice, it's not an identity. Confusing choices with identities causes problems because it can lead people like your parents or those even less informed than your parents to have the false belief that being gay/bi/ace/trans/etc is also a choice. Be clear about what is an identity (beyond your control) and what is a preference/choice so that people understand the difference.

It sounds like your parents are learning as they go. Be patient with them. This is all new to them and they didn't grow up with these kinds of things talked about the way you have. one I would include is MASTER by Mariah the Scientist. I was surprised I liked this album, but it tells the story of Mariah the Scientist overcoming self doubts and a toxic relationship in a very R&B/pop way. She reminded me a lot of Jhene Aiko but not as psychedelic. Other comparisons could be SZA, who I absolutely ADORE. Anyway, the album is really great, and it has some bangers. The opener "Note to Self" is all about airing your dirty laundry with yourself, and you'll love the song even more when you figure out the word she's spelling out if you're anything like me. Two other tracks that stood out to me were "Beetlejuice" and "Not a Love Song". "Beetlejuice" is a straight up banger that depicts the murky waters of a toxic, complicated relationship, and "Not A Love Song" is my personal favorite from the album. It closes the album with Mariah reminiscing on herself, her ex, their relationship, and what her momma said about him just to name some things, and it's been one of my favorite songs recently. It might not be everyone's cup of tea if you don't love breakup/sadder/insecure music, but Mariah sells it, singing with confidence even as she talks about her pitfalls. Some might find it a little simplistic too, but I think it's definitely a very good album that almost no one is talking about.
